Foundations of Data Science Project - Diabetes Analysis¶

Context¶

Diabetes is one of the most frequent diseases worldwide and the number of diabetic patients are growing over the years. The main cause of diabetes remains unknown, yet scientists believe that both genetic factors and environmental lifestyle play a major role in diabetes.

A few years ago research was done on a tribe in America which is called the Pima tribe. In this tribe, it was found that the ladies are prone to diabetes very early. Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients were females at least 21 years old of Pima tribe.

Objective¶

Here, we are analyzing different aspects of Diabetes in the Pima Diabetes Analysis by doing Exploratory Data Analysis.

Data Dictionary¶

The dataset has the following information:

  • Pregnancies: Number of times pregnant
  • Glucose: Plasma glucose concentration over 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test
  • BloodPressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
  • SkinThickness: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  • Insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)
  • BMI: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)
  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction: A function that scores the likelihood of diabetes based on family history.
  • Age: Age in years
  • Outcome: Class variable (0: a person is not diabetic or 1: a person is diabetic)

Ans 1:¶

Numpy¶

Short for Numerical Python, numpy is a library containing many functions useful in scientific computing and notably the datatype ndarray (n-dimensional array).

Pandas¶

Pandas derives its name from Panel Data and is another package useful in scientific computing. It is dependant on numpy and the main datatypes Pandas brings are the DataFrame and Series.

Matplotlib.pyplot¶

Matplotlib is a package for data visualization which is very flexible. Pyplot is a collection of functions within Matplotlib and is usually sufficient to import rather than the full Matplotlib library.

Seaborn¶

Seaborn is a plotting package which depends on Matplotlib and adds plot types to the baseline collection. The mantra around matplotlib and seaborn is "Matplotlib makes easy thing easy and hard things possible. Seaborn makes a selection of hard things easy."

Ans 9:¶

count: The total number of entries in that column. Ex. There are 768 data points regarding the glucose level in the patients.

mean: The average value in that column type, calculated as $\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_i$ where n=768 is the number of entries and $x_i$ is the value of entry $i$. Ex. If we added up the total glucose level for all patients and divide by the number of patients in this dataset, we find an average glucose level of approximately 121.68.

std = Standard Deviation, $\sigma$: A statistic describing how dispersed the dataset is. If we take $\mu$ as the calculated mean and use the variables as described above, then $\sigma=\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=0}^n ( x_i - \mu )^2}{n}}$. In a Gaussian distribution, approximately 68% of the data fall within the range $\mu-\sigma$ to $\mu+\sigma$. Ex. With regard to glucose level in this dataset, $\sigma\approx30.44$.

min = minimum value: This is the smallest value in the dataset for the given variable. Ex. There is at least one patient who had a glucose level of 44 and no patients with a glucose level less than 44.

25% = First Quartile: This is the threshold at which 25% of the data have smaller values. Ex. 25% of the patients (192) have a glucose level below 99.75.

50% = Second Quartile = Median: This is the threshold at which half of the data have smaller values and half of the data have larger values. Ex. 50% of the patients (384) have a glucose level less than 117.00.

75% = Third Quartile: This is the threshold at which three quarters of the data have smaller values. Ex. 75% of the patients (576) have glucose levels below 140.25.

max = maximum value: This is the largest value in the dataset for the gien variable. Ex. There is at least one patient who had a glucose level of 199 and there are no patients who had a glucose level higher than 199.

Ans 15:¶

Single Variable Plots:¶

Glucose: Patients with higher levels of glucose are more strongly associated with a positive outcome than patients lower levels. The glucose distribution for patients with a positive outcome appears to be made from two overlapping Gaussians with peaks at around 140 and 180 while the distribution for negative outcomes is tracks well with a Gaussian centered around 180. In the negative distribution, a small secondary peak is visible around 180 as well, though it is much smaller than the 180 peak in the positive distribution. It may be interesting to investigate the origin of the peak at 180 to see if there is a reason why it is so much more pronounced in the positive patients than the negative ones.

Skin Thickness: The distribution of skin thickness for patients with positive and negative outcomes are similar in shape, and both appear to be made from multiple underlying Gaussians. For both positive and negative patients, the main peak is around a skin thickness of 20, and in both cases the drop off on the high side is interrupted by a secondary distribution.

Diabetes Pedigree Function (DPF): For both positive and negative patients, the DPF is peaked around 0.25, though the positive distribution is shifted slightly to larger values. There is a steep dropoff to the small side for both the positive and negative distributions, and on the high side both distributions fall slower than would be expected for a Gaussian. Proportionally more mositive patients stay with higher values of DPF than do negative patients.

Scatter Plots:¶

Glucose v Skin Thickness: The histograms for skin thickness in positive and negative patients are very similar, and adding glucose to make a scatter plot does little to obviously differentiate the two patient types. As would be expected from the glucose histogram, patients with higher glucose levels are more likely to be positive and patients with lower glucose levels are more likely to be negative, but there is no clear relationship between glucose level and skin thickness. There is one very notable outlier which has a high glucose level and high skin thickness and this person tested as positive.

Glucose v DPF: The trend of higher glucose values corresponding to higher probabilities of positivity is also visible in this scatter distribution, but there is again little obvious correlation between glucose level and DPF for positive or negative patients. There are a handful of positive outliers with relatively high glucose levals and high DPF but there is also a negative outlier with high glucose and high DPF.

Skin Thickness v DPF: Skin thickness and DPF both have very similar positive patient and negative patient shapes in their individual histograms, so it is unsurprising that making a scatter plot of the two variables has substantial overlap between positive and negative patients. While most of the outliers are positive patients with relatively thick skin and a very high DPF, it is also notable that the patient with the thickest skin was also positive and yet had a DPF close to the mean.

Ans 16:¶

One obvious feature that stands out in both the positive and negative outcome distributions is that there is a disproportionately high number of patients with an insulin level of exactly 79 when compared to any other insulin level, even neighboring values. This is true across glucose levels and may indicate that 79 is some sort of a default value assigned when the data was taken. It is most visible in the histograms plotted above the scatter plots.

Comparing insulin levels to glucose levels, there appears to be a weak correlation between the two variables in negative patients, with higher glucose levels corresponding to higher insulin levels. In patients who tested positive, glucose levels show minimal correlation to insulin levels, and patients with high glucose are about as likely to have high insulin as they are low.

It is visible in these plots, though more apparent in the KDE distributions above, that negative patients tend to have lower glucose levels (clustered in the 80-140 range) than patients who tested positive (distributed roughly evenly in the 100-180 range).

Ans 19:¶

The Interquartile Range (IQR) is defined as the range of the data containing half of the data points, centered around the median value. Numerically, this corresponds to finding the range between the first and third quartiles of the data.

This may be a useful number when trying to understand the spread in the data of a distribution and may be used as an alternative to the standard deviation.

The IQR is the boxed part of a box plot.

Ans 20:¶

As can be seen in the correlation matrix plots above, none of the variables in this dataset are very strongly correlated, where strong correlation is defined as having a correlation coefficient $r>0.7$ Of the most correlated variables, the pair (Age / Number of Pregnancies) has a correlation of 0.54 overall and seems intuitive that the older the patient is, the more likely they are to have had a larger number of children. When we compare these correlations between positive and negative patients, the general trend is true for both classes, but the correlation is stronger in negative patients. This indicates that negative patients are more likely to have more children with time than their positive counterparts.

Other leading pairs are (BMI / Skin Thickness), which indicate people with a higher BMI also tend to have thicker skin. Separating the dataset into positive and negative patients, we can see that the trend is less strong among those who are positive, meaning patients who are positive tend to have a smaller amount of skin thickening as their BMI increases than those who are negative.

Continuing with the BMI, when we look at how it tracks with insulin levels, the results are interesting. There is a (weak) correlation between BMI and insulin levels (0.24) for negative patients, but for positive patients, the correlation nearly disappears (0.02).

Another large difference between the populations can be seen by comparing the correlations between skin thickness and the Diabetes Pedigree Function. For negative patients, there is essentially no correlation (0.05) but for positive patients, there is a small positive correlation (0.24).
